The following method in OfBizCustomFieldValuePersister does not handle updating a custom field as an atomic action.

{code:java}
public void updateValues(CustomField field, Long issueId, PersistenceFieldType persistenceFieldType, Collection values, String parentKey) {
        final List<GenericValue> GVs = getValuesForTypeAndParent(field, issueId, parentKey);
        if (values != null && !values.isEmpty()) {
            createValuesInt(field, issueId, persistenceFieldType, values, parentKey);
        }
        delegator.removeAll(GVs);
    }
{code}

One issue we've run into is when removing elements from a custom field concurrently values can become duplicated, resulting in duplicate rows in the database.

Scenario:
* Three custom field values A~0~, B~0~, C~0~.
* Two clients 1 and 2

1. Client 1 and Client 2 simultaneously attempt to delete C, as such they may both attempt to update the custom field contain only A and B.


||Client 1||Client 2||description||
||getValuesForTypeAndParent|| ||Client 1 acquires original values in the field A~0~, B~0~, C~0~||
|| ||getValuesForTypeAndParent||Client 2 acquires original values in the field A~0~, B~0~, C~0~||
||createValuesInt|| ||Client 1 writes new values A~1~, B~1~||
|| ||createValuesInt||Client 2 writes new values A~2~, B~2~||
||removeAll|| ||Client 1 removes A~0~, B~0~, C~0~||
|| ||removeAll||Client 2 removes A~0~, B~0~, C~0~||

As a result we now have A~1~, B~1~, A~2~, B~2~ in our custom field when we should only have one A and one B.

Affects all versions.

P.S it seems subscript is broken...

